text.tspan: The Sellers shall deliver the vessel to the Buyers with everything belonging to her on board, on shore and on order. All spare partsand all spare equipment belonging to the vessel at the time of the inspection, used or unused, whether on board or not shall becomethe buyer’s property together with the broached / unbroached stores and provision.Forwarding charges, if any, shall be for the Buyers account. The Sellers have the right to take ashore crockery, plate, cutlery, linenand other articles bearing the Seller’s flag or name, provided they replace same with similar unmarked items. Library, forms, etc.exclusively for use in the Sellers’ vessel shall be excluded without compensation. Captain’s, officers’ and crew’s personal belongingsincluding slop chest to be excluded from the sale. The Buyers shall take over all remaining bunkers and unused / unbroachedlubricating oils in storage tanks and drums and pay extra for same at the prevailing prices.b) The vessel with everything belonging to her shall be at the Seller’s risk and expense until she is delivered to the Buyers, but subjectto the conditions of this contract, she shall be delivered and taken over as she is at the time of the inspection, fair wear and tearexpected. However, the vessel shall be delivered with present class free of recommendations. The sellers shall notify theClassification Society of any matters coming to their knowledge which may result in withdrawal of the vessel’s class or of arecommendation relating to her class.7) As you will note from the above clauses, any damages or defect which may occur from the time you join the vessel should becarefully noted and catalogued with date and time of occurrence. If you can send information to the head office well and good, if not,this information should be handed over to the attending Superintendent on his arrival on board so that he may take up the matter withthe Seller. You should not make an issue with the ship’s staff as it would make your life uncomfortable.8) If a machinery breakdown has taken place and the ship’s staff have repaired same using spares from the ship’s stock, you shouldmake a list and report to the attending superintendent.9) Since the spare parts already ordered by the Seller, but not yet delivered, also become the property of the buyers, make a note ofany such evidence that you may find on board.10) At the time of delivery of the vessel Seller has to handover to us a complete inventory of spares, tools and stores for eachdepartment. Persuade the ship’s staff to start on this job well in time and show some personal interest so that the inventories aremethodical and accurate.11) Major spares for main engine and auxiliary engine like Piston, Liner, Cylinder cover and mounting, Fuel pumps and injector, if notnew, must be thoroughly inspected and calibrated to ensure that they are not condemned ones.12) Apart from spares, you should keep looking for any deficiency which may affect the Class or any of the Statutory certificates sothat these can be taken up with the Seller either to make good or for cash compensation.13) It is usual that when a ship owner decides to sell his ship, he curtails all expenses on repairs, spares and stores. Therefore, oftenwe have to takeover vessels, which need urgent supplies or repairs. You should prepare a list of defects and our usual requisitions forspares and stores with all relevant data so that these things can be quickly attended to as soon as we takeover the vessel. As youare aware, we make separate requisitions for supply of chemicals, gases / electrodes / joints, lubricating oils/greases and stores(department-wise) including linen, crockery, cutlery etc separate requisitions for charts / nautical publications and medicines arerequired.14) As you know that lubricating oils have to be arranged from head office and sometimes we change the supplier. As soon as youjoin the vessel it is necessary that you advise the name of the supplier and the grades used with ROBs for all services but essentiallyfor main engine crankcase oil, main engine cylinder oil and auxiliary engine crankcase oil. Please also advise daily consumption forthese services.15) Similarly, we have to make advance arrangements for expensive items of stores like paints, mooring ropes and wires. Pleaseadvise head office condition, ROBs and requirements well in advance. Same goes for supply of stores like chemicals and gases.16) Your third function is to spend as much time as possible to familiarize yourself with the ships operation and gather data of itsequipments as others on board would be seeking your guidance when we takeover the vessel. You should pay special attention tothe following:a) Procedure for loading / unloading (Please note consumptions).b) Ballasting / deballasting (Please note consumptions)c) Operation and correct function of all cargo handling / towing equipmentd) Mooring / unmooring operationsg) Operation of deck cranes / deck machinery.h) Main engine and engine room requirements – enquire if for some reason equipment is under performing or deliberately kept atlower level of performance than designed. Maneuvering operation, getting the plant ready prior start up and procedures after shutdown of main engine. Changing over main engine and aux. Engine from DO to HO and vice versa.i) Check all past logbooks and past performances.j) Requisitions for essential spare parts should be sent to us soonest possible as required for example:Fuel injectors for main engine, aux. enginePiston rings for main engine, aux engineTurbocharger bearingsk) In the engine room, go through vessel’s records / reports and take note of any recurring problem areas and advise.l) Check all records onboard of vessel’s equipment such as cylinder liner wear rate, main engine deflection, aux. engine deflectionetc. If opportunity arises and ship’s staff are taking deflections, would suggest you make an effort to enter the crankcase and checkthe reference marks of crank joined to web.m) Take note of any pumps and equipment, which present staff are hesitant to operate and advise us so that the equipment can betested prior delivery.n) Advice we of any controllers and equipments, which are presently out of order and whether vessel has any outstanding requisitionsfor reinstating thes13.2ANNEX 2 TECHNICAL REPORTS
